Remote Work Policy
Overview
Acme Corp supports flexible work arrangements. This policy defines the rules and expectations for employees working remotely, whether full-time or in a hybrid capacity.
Eligibility
•
Employees who have completed at least 90 days of employment are eligible to apply for remote work arrangements.
•
Remote work eligibility is determined by the employee's role, performance history, and manager approval.
•
Roles that require physical presence (e.g., on-site IT support, lab technicians) are not eligible for remote work.
Types of Remote Work
•
Hybrid Remote: Employees work from the office at least 3 days per week and may work remotely the remaining days.
•
Full-Time Remote: Available only for designated remote roles or by special approval from VP-level management and HR.
•
Temporary Remote: Short-term remote arrangements (up to 30 days) may be approved by a direct manager without HR involvement.
Application Process
1.
Employee submits a Remote Work Request form via the HR portal.
2.
Direct manager reviews and approves or denies within 5 business days.
3.
HR reviews approved requests and adds the arrangement to the employee's file.
4.
Remote work agreements are reviewed every 6 months.
Expectations While Working Remotely
•
Employees must be available and responsive during core hours: 9:00 AM – 3:00 PM in their local time zone.
•
Employees must attend all scheduled meetings via video unless otherwise agreed.
•
Response to messages (Slack, email) is expected within 2 hours during core hours.
•
Employees must maintain a professional and distraction-free workspace.
•
Work hours must still total 40 hours per week for full-time employees.
Equipment and Technology
•
Acme Corp provides a company laptop, monitor, keyboard, and mouse to approved remote employees.
•
Employees are responsible for providing a reliable internet connection (minimum 25 Mbps download speed recommended).
•
The company will reimburse up to $50/month for internet costs for full-time remote employees, with a receipt submitted through the expense system.
•
All company equipment must be used in accordance with the IT Security Policy and returned upon termination.
Security Requirements
•
Employees must use a company-approved VPN when accessing internal systems remotely.
•
Public Wi-Fi networks (cafes, airports, hotels) must not be used without the VPN active.
•
Company devices must have automatic screen lock enabled (maximum 5-minute timeout).
•
Employees must not allow family members or third parties to use company devices.
Performance and Accountability
•
Remote employees are held to the same performance standards as in-office employees.
•
Managers will conduct monthly check-ins with remote employees to review workload and productivity.
•
Poor performance or failure to meet remote work expectations may result in revocation of remote work privileges.
Revocation of Remote Work Privileges
•
Remote work arrangements may be revoked at any time with 2 weeks' notice from the manager or HR.
•
Immediate revocation may occur in cases of security violations or serious misconduct.
Contact
For remote work requests or questions, contact hr@acmecorp.com.
Expense Reimbursement Policy
Overview
This policy establishes guidelines for submitting and approving business-related expense reimbursements at Acme Corp. All employees are expected to spend company funds responsibly and in accordance with this policy.
Eligible Expenses
The following expenses are eligible for reimbursement when incurred for legitimate business purposes:
•
Business travel (flights, trains, rental cars, taxis, rideshares)
•
Hotel accommodations during business travel
•
Business meals and client entertainment
•
Office supplies purchased for remote work
•
Conference and event registration fees
•
Professional development courses and certifications
•
Internet reimbursement for full-time remote employees (up to $50/month)
Expense Limits
Meals
•
Breakfast: Up to $20 per person
•
Lunch: Up to $30 per person
•
Dinner: Up to $60 per person
•
Client entertainment meals: Up to $100 per person (requires manager pre-approval)
Travel
•
Economy class flights are required for domestic travel and international flights under 6 hours.
•
Business class may be approved for international flights over 6 hours with VP approval.
•
Hotel accommodation: Up to $200/night in standard cities; up to $300/night in high-cost cities (New York, San Francisco, London, etc.).
•
Rental cars: Economy or compact class only, unless unavailable.
•
Mileage reimbursement: $0.67 per mile for personal vehicle use (IRS standard rate).
Other
•
Conference registration: Up to $2,000 per event (pre-approval required above $500).
•
Professional certifications: Up to $1,000 per year per employee (pre-approval required).
•
Office supplies: Up to $100 per month without pre-approval.
Non-Reimbursable Expenses
The following expenses will NOT be reimbursed:
•
Personal entertainment (movies, sporting events, unless a client is present)
•
Alcohol (unless part of an approved client dinner — limit $30/person for alcohol)
•
Traffic fines, parking tickets, or other penalties
•
Lost or stolen personal items
•
Upgrades to flights or hotels not pre-approved
•
Expenses for family members or non-employees (unless explicitly approved)
•
Gym memberships or personal wellness items
•
Expenses submitted more than 60 days after the date incurred
Submission Process
1.
Log in to the Expense Portal at expenses.acmecorp.com.
2.
Create a new expense report for each business trip or expense period.
3.
Upload receipts for all expenses over $25. Receipts are not required for items under $25, but a description is mandatory.
4.
Submit the report to your direct manager for approval.
5.
Manager approval must be completed within 5 business days of submission.
6.
Finance processes approved reports within 10 business days and reimburses via direct deposit.
Pre-Approval Requirements
Pre-approval is required for:
•
Any single expense over $500
•
International travel
•
Client entertainment over $50/person
•
Conference registrations over $500
•
Any expense not covered in the eligible expenses list above
Pre-approval requests must be submitted to your manager at least 3 business days before the expense is incurred.
Corporate Credit Cards
•
Employees in the Sales, Marketing, and Senior Management teams may be issued a corporate credit card.
•
Corporate cards must only be used for approved business expenses.
•
Monthly statements must be reconciled and submitted to Finance by the 5th of each month.
•
Misuse of a corporate card may result in disciplinary action, up to and including termination.
Disputes and Questions
For questions about expense eligibility or reimbursement status, contact finance@acmecorp.com.
IT Security Policy
Overview
This policy establishes the rules and responsibilities for protecting Acme Corp's information systems, data, and digital assets. All employees, contractors, and third-party vendors with access to company systems must comply with this policy.
Password Requirements
•
Passwords must be at least 12 characters long.
•
Passwords must include at least one uppercase letter, one lowercase letter, one number, and one special character (e.g., !, @, #, $).
•
Passwords must be changed every 90 days.
•
Employees must not reuse any of their last 10 passwords.
•
Default or temporary passwords must be changed immediately upon first login.
•
Passwords must never be shared with anyone, including IT staff. Acme Corp IT will never ask for your password.
Multi-Factor Authentication (MFA)
•
MFA is mandatory for all company systems, including email, HR portal, expense portal, and all cloud applications.
•
Employees must use an approved authenticator app (Google Authenticator, Microsoft Authenticator, or Okta Verify).
•
SMS-based MFA is permitted only as a backup method.
•
MFA devices must be reported lost or compromised to IT immediately at security@acmecorp.com.
Device Security
•
All company-issued devices (laptops, phones, tablets) must have full-disk encryption enabled.
•
Automatic screen lock must be set to 5 minutes or less.
•
Operating systems and applications must be kept up to date. IT pushes mandatory updates — employees must not delay or dismiss them.
•
Company devices must have the company-approved antivirus/EDR software installed at all times.
•
Employees must not install unauthorized software on company devices. Approved software is available in the Company App Store.
•
Personal devices may be used for work email only if enrolled in the Mobile Device Management (MDM) system.
Network Security
•
Employees must use the company VPN when accessing internal systems from outside the office.
•
Public Wi-Fi must not be used without the VPN active.
•
Employees must not connect unauthorized devices (personal routers, smart devices) to the corporate network.
•
Home routers used for remote work must use WPA2 or WPA3 encryption.
Data Handling
•
Confidential company data must not be stored on personal devices or personal cloud storage (Google Drive personal, Dropbox personal, etc.).
•
Approved cloud storage includes Microsoft OneDrive (company account) and SharePoint.
•
Customer data must never be shared externally without authorization from the Data Privacy Officer.
•
Physical documents containing sensitive information must be shredded when no longer needed.
Email and Phishing
•
Employees must not click links or open attachments from unknown or suspicious senders.
•
Suspected phishing emails must be reported immediately using the "Report Phishing" button in Outlook, or forwarded to security@acmecorp.com.
•
Employees must not use personal email accounts for company business.
•
Bulk or marketing emails must not be sent from personal company email accounts — use the marketing platform.
Incident Reporting
•
Any suspected security incident (lost device, phishing click, unauthorized access, data breach) must be reported to IT Security within 1 hour of discovery.
•
Contact: security@acmecorp.com or call the IT Security Hotline at ext. 5555.
•
Employees must not attempt to investigate or resolve security incidents on their own.
Acceptable Use
•
Company systems are for business use. Limited personal use is permitted as long as it does not interfere with work or violate any policies.
•
Prohibited activities include: accessing illegal content, downloading pirated software, using company systems for personal financial gain, or any activity that violates applicable law.
Violations
•
Violations of this policy may result in disciplinary action, up to and including termination.
•
Serious violations (intentional data breaches, sharing credentials) will be referred to legal counsel and may result in criminal prosecution.
Contact
For security questions or to report an incident, contact security@acmecorp.com or call ext. 5555.
Code of Conduct Policy
Overview
Acme Corp is committed to maintaining a respectful, inclusive, and professional workplace. This Code of Conduct applies to all employees, contractors, and partners in all work-related settings, including the office, remote work environments, business travel, and company events.
Core Values
All employees are expected to embody Acme Corp's core values:
•
Integrity: Act honestly and transparently in all interactions.
•
Respect: Treat every person with dignity regardless of their role, background, or identity.
•
Accountability: Take ownership of your work and its outcomes.
•
Collaboration: Work constructively with colleagues, clients, and partners.
•
Excellence: Strive for high-quality work and continuous improvement.
Professional Behavior
Employees are expected to:
•
Communicate respectfully in all written and verbal communications.
•
Meet deadlines and commitments, or proactively communicate delays.
•
Maintain confidentiality of sensitive company, client, and colleague information.
•
Dress appropriately for their work environment (see Dress Code Policy).
•
Represent Acme Corp professionally when interacting with clients, partners, and the public.
Anti-Harassment Policy
Acme Corp has zero tolerance for harassment of any kind, including:
•
Sexual harassment (unwanted advances, inappropriate comments, or touching)
•
Bullying or intimidation
•
Discrimination based on race, gender, age, religion, nationality, disability, sexual orientation, or any other protected characteristic
•
Hostile or threatening behavior
•
Retaliation against anyone who reports harassment or participates in an investigation
Harassment includes conduct in person, over email, in chat platforms (Slack), on social media, and at company events.
Reporting Violations
•
Employees who experience or witness a Code of Conduct violation should report it to their manager, HR, or via the anonymous Ethics Hotline at ethics.acmecorp.com.
•
All reports will be investigated promptly and confidentially.
•
Retaliation against any employee who makes a good-faith report is strictly prohibited and is itself a violation of this policy.
Conflict of Interest
•
Employees must disclose any personal, financial, or professional relationships that could create a conflict of interest with their duties at Acme Corp.
•
Employees must not make purchasing decisions, hiring decisions, or business arrangements that personally benefit themselves, family members, or close associates.
•
Conflicts of interest must be disclosed in writing to HR and the employee's manager.
Gifts and Entertainment
•
Employees may accept gifts from clients or vendors valued at no more than $50.
•
Gifts exceeding $50 must be disclosed to HR and either returned or donated to charity.
•
Employees must not solicit gifts or entertainment from clients or vendors.
•
Cash gifts of any amount are never permitted.
Social Media
•
Employees must not share confidential company information, client data, or unreleased product information on social media.
•
Employees must not make statements on social media that could damage Acme Corp's reputation.
•
Employees who wish to post publicly about Acme Corp should include a disclaimer that their views are their own.
•
The Communications team manages all official Acme Corp social media accounts.
Disciplinary Actions
Violations of this Code of Conduct may result in:
•
Verbal or written warning
•
Performance improvement plan
•
Suspension without pay
•
Termination of employment
•
Legal action where applicable
The severity of the action will depend on the nature and seriousness of the violation.
Contact
To report a concern or ask questions about the Code of Conduct, contact hr@acmecorp.com or use the anonymous Ethics Hotline at ethics.acmecorp.com.
Paid Time Off (PTO) & Vacation Policy
Overview
This policy outlines the Paid Time Off (PTO) and vacation entitlements for all full-time and part-time employees at Acme Corp.
Eligibility
•
All full-time employees (working 40 hours/week) are eligible for PTO starting from their first day of employment.
•
Part-time employees (working 20–39 hours/week) receive prorated PTO based on hours worked.
•
Contractors and temporary staff are not eligible for PTO under this policy.
PTO Accrual
•
Year 1–2: Employees accrue 15 days (120 hours) of PTO per year, at a rate of 1.25 days per month.
•
Year 3–5: Employees accrue 18 days (144 hours) of PTO per year, at a rate of 1.5 days per month.
•
Year 6+: Employees accrue 22 days (176 hours) of PTO per year, at a rate of approximately 1.83 days per month.
•
PTO begins accruing from the employee's first day of work.
Vacation Requests
•
Employees must submit vacation requests at least 5 business days in advance for requests of 1–3 days.
•
Requests of 4 or more consecutive days must be submitted at least 2 weeks in advance.
•
Requests must be submitted through the HR portal and approved by the direct manager.
•
Approval is subject to business needs and team availability.
PTO Carryover
•
Employees may carry over a maximum of 10 unused PTO days into the next calendar year.
•
Any unused PTO exceeding 10 days will be forfeited at the end of the calendar year (December 31).
•
There is no cash payout for forfeited PTO days.
PTO Payout on Termination
•
Upon voluntary resignation with at least 2 weeks' notice, employees will be paid out for all accrued but unused PTO.
•
Employees terminated for cause will not receive a PTO payout.
•
PTO payout is calculated based on the employee's current hourly rate.
Sick Days
•
Sick leave is separate from PTO. Employees receive 10 sick days per calendar year.
•
Sick days do not accrue and do not carry over to the next year.
•
Employees must notify their manager before 9:00 AM on the day of their absence.
•
A doctor's note may be required for absences exceeding 3 consecutive sick days.
Public Holidays
•
Employees are entitled to all 11 federal public holidays as paid days off.
•
If a public holiday falls on a weekend, the nearest weekday will be observed.
Unpaid Leave
•
Employees who have exhausted their PTO may request unpaid leave, subject to manager and HR approval.
•
Unpaid leave requests must be submitted in writing to HR at least 1 week in advance.
Contact
For questions about PTO balances or requests, contact hr@acmecorp.com or visit the HR portal.
Performance Review & Promotion Policy
Overview
Acme Corp conducts regular performance reviews to support employee growth, align individual goals with company objectives, and determine compensation adjustments and promotions.
Review Cycles
•
Annual Review: Conducted in December each year for all employees. Results take effect January 1 of the following year.
•
Mid-Year Check-In: Conducted in June as an informal progress review. Not tied to compensation changes.
•
Probationary Review: New employees receive a formal review at the end of their 90-day probationary period.
•
Off-Cycle Reviews: May be conducted at any time to address performance issues or exceptional contributions.
Review Process
1.
Self-Assessment: Employee completes a self-evaluation form in the HR portal at least 2 weeks before the scheduled review meeting.
2.
Manager Assessment: Direct manager completes an evaluation of the employee based on goals, competencies, and overall performance.
3.
Peer Feedback (optional): For senior roles (Level 4+), 360-degree peer feedback may be collected.
4.
Review Meeting: Manager and employee meet to discuss the evaluation, feedback, and goals for the coming year.
5.
HR Review: HR reviews all performance ratings for calibration and consistency across teams.
6.
Outcome Communication: Final ratings and any compensation changes are communicated by January 15.
Performance Ratings
Rating
Description
5 – Exceptional
Consistently exceeds all expectations; significant impact beyond the role
4 – Exceeds Expectations
Regularly surpasses goals; strong contributor
3 – Meets Expectations
Reliably meets all goals; solid performance
2 – Needs Improvement
Partially meets expectations; improvement required
1 – Unsatisfactory
Fails to meet core expectations; immediate action required
Compensation Adjustments
•
Employees rated 3 (Meets Expectations) are eligible for a cost-of-living adjustment (COLA) of up to 3%.
•
Employees rated 4 (Exceeds Expectations) are eligible for a merit increase of 3–6%.
•
Employees rated 5 (Exceptional) are eligible for a merit increase of 6–10% and may be considered for a spot bonus.
•
Employees rated 1 or 2 are not eligible for a salary increase and may be placed on a Performance Improvement Plan (PIP).
Performance Improvement Plan (PIP)
•
A PIP is issued when an employee receives a rating of 1 or 2, or when ongoing performance issues are identified outside of review cycles.
•
The PIP outlines specific, measurable improvement goals and a timeline of 30, 60, or 90 days.
•
A follow-up review is conducted at the end of the PIP period.
•
Failure to meet PIP goals may result in further disciplinary action, including termination.
Promotions
•
Promotions are based on demonstrated performance, readiness, and business need.
•
Employees are typically eligible for promotion after 12 months in their current role.
•
Managers may nominate employees for promotion during the annual review cycle.
•
All promotions above Level 5 require approval from VP-level management and HR.
•
Promotions typically include a title change and a salary increase of 10–20% depending on the level.
Goal Setting
•
Employees and managers must set 3–5 SMART goals at the beginning of each year.
•
Goals must be entered into the HR portal by January 31.
•
Goals are reviewed and updated at the mid-year check-in if business priorities change.
Contact
For questions about performance reviews or promotions, contact hr@acmecorp.com.
Employee Onboarding Policy
Overview
This policy describes the onboarding process for all new employees joining Acme Corp. A structured onboarding experience ensures new hires are set up for success from day one.
Before the First Day (Pre-Boarding)
•
HR will send a welcome email within 24 hours of the signed offer letter, including:
o
New hire paperwork (tax forms, direct deposit setup, benefits enrollment)
o
IT setup instructions and equipment delivery tracking
o
First-day schedule and manager contact information
o
Access to the Acme Corp Employee Handbook
•
New hires must complete all paperwork at least 3 business days before their start date.
•
IT will provision accounts (email, Slack, HR portal) 1 business day before the start date.
•
A company laptop will be shipped to remote employees or available for pickup at the office for in-office employees.
Day One
•
New employees report to reception (or join a video onboarding call if remote) at 9:00 AM.
•
HR will conduct a 1-hour orientation covering:
o
Company overview, mission, and values
o
Key policies (this document, Code of Conduct, IT Security, PTO)
o
Benefits enrollment walkthrough
o
HR portal and expense portal access
•
IT will conduct a 30-minute device setup session.
•
The direct manager will introduce the new hire to the immediate team.
•
A buddy (peer mentor) will be assigned to help the new hire navigate their first 30 days.
First Week
•
The manager will schedule daily 15-minute check-ins for the first week.
•
New hires should complete all mandatory training modules in the Learning Management System (LMS) within their first 5 business days. Required modules include:
o
Code of Conduct Training
o
IT Security Awareness Training
o
Data Privacy Training
o
Workplace Safety Training
•
The new hire will attend team meetings and be introduced to cross-functional stakeholders.
•
HR will check in at the end of Week 1 to answer any questions.
First 30 Days
•
Manager and new hire will set 30-day onboarding goals during the first week.
•
New hire should complete all role-specific technical onboarding (tools, systems, processes).
•
New hire attends a New Employee Welcome session hosted by the CEO (held monthly).
•
Buddy check-ins happen at least twice per week.
First 90 Days (Probationary Period)
•
New employees are on a 90-day probationary period.
•
During this period, either the employee or Acme Corp may end the employment relationship with 1 week's notice (instead of the standard 2 weeks).
•
At the end of 90 days, the manager conducts a formal probationary review.
•
Successful completion of probation grants full employee status and access to all benefits.
Benefits Enrollment
•
New employees must enroll in health, dental, and vision insurance within 30 days of their start date.
•
Enrollment after 30 days is only permitted during the annual Open Enrollment period (November each year) or after a qualifying life event (marriage, birth of a child, etc.).
•
401(k) enrollment is available immediately; company matching begins after 90 days of employment.
Required Documentation
New employees must provide the following within their first day:
•
Government-issued photo ID
•
Social Security card or equivalent tax documentation
•
Work authorization documentation (for non-US citizens)
•
Signed copy of the Confidentiality and IP Assignment Agreement
Remote Employee Onboarding
•
Remote new hires follow the same process via video calls and digital document signing.
•
Equipment will be shipped and must arrive before the start date. Contact IT at it@acmecorp.com if equipment is delayed.
•
Remote new hires are encouraged to visit the office within their first 60 days for an in-person team introduction.
Contact
For onboarding questions, contact hr@acmecorp.com or your assigned HR Business Partner.
Parental Leave Policy
Overview
Acme Corp is committed to supporting employees during one of life's most significant milestones. This policy outlines paid and unpaid leave entitlements for employees welcoming a new child through birth, adoption, or foster placement.
Eligibility
•
All full-time employees who have completed at least 12 months of continuous employment are eligible for paid parental leave.
•
Employees with less than 12 months of service are eligible for unpaid parental leave only, in accordance with applicable law (e.g., FMLA in the US).
•
Part-time employees working 20+ hours/week are eligible for prorated paid leave.
Paid Parental Leave Entitlement
Primary Caregiver (Birthing Parent or Designated Primary Caregiver)
•
16 weeks of fully paid parental leave.
•
Leave may begin up to 2 weeks before the expected due date.
•
Pay during leave is 100% of the employee's base salary.
Secondary Caregiver (Non-Birthing Parent, Co-Parent, or Partner)
•
6 weeks of fully paid parental leave.
•
Leave must begin within 6 months of the child's birth, adoption, or placement.
Adoption and Foster Placement
•
Primary caregivers adopting or fostering a child under age 18 receive 12 weeks of fully paid leave.
•
Secondary caregivers receive 6 weeks of fully paid leave.
•
Leave must begin within 30 days of the child's placement.
Additional Unpaid Leave
•
After exhausting paid parental leave, employees may take up to an additional 12 weeks of unpaid leave.
•
Total parental leave (paid + unpaid) may not exceed 28 weeks for primary caregivers or 18 weeks for secondary caregivers.
Notice Requirements
•
Employees must notify HR and their manager of their intent to take parental leave at least 30 days before the expected start date.
•
In cases of early birth or emergency placement, notification must occur as soon as reasonably possible.
•
Notice must be provided in writing via the HR portal.
Job Protection
•
Employees returning from parental leave within the paid leave period are guaranteed to return to their same or equivalent role at the same salary.
•
Employees taking extended unpaid leave beyond the paid period are subject to role availability, but Acme Corp will make reasonable efforts to return them to an equivalent position.
Benefits Continuation
•
Health, dental, and vision insurance coverage continues during paid parental leave at the same employee contribution rates.
•
401(k) contributions by the company continue during paid leave.
•
PTO does not accrue during unpaid leave periods.
Returning to Work
•
Employees must confirm their return-to-work date with HR at least 2 weeks in advance.
•
A phased return-to-work schedule (e.g., starting at 60% capacity for 2 weeks) may be arranged with manager and HR approval.
•
Employees who do not return after parental leave may be required to repay a prorated portion of the paid leave received, as outlined in their parental leave agreement.
Interaction with Other Leave
•
Parental leave runs concurrently with FMLA (Family and Medical Leave Act) leave where applicable.
•
Employees may not use PTO to extend their parental leave period beyond the maximums stated in this policy.
Confidentiality
All parental leave requests and related medical information are kept strictly confidential and shared only with HR and relevant managers on a need-to-know basis.
Contact
To initiate a parental leave request, contact hr@acmecorp.com or your assigned HR Business Partner.
Attendance & Punctuality Policy
Overview
Regular attendance and punctuality are essential to maintaining productivity and a collaborative work environment at Acme Corp. This policy outlines expectations for attendance and the procedures for reporting and managing absences.
Core Hours
•
Standard office hours are 9:00 AM to 5:00 PM, Monday through Friday, in the employee's local time zone.
•
Core collaboration hours (when all employees must be available) are 10:00 AM to 3:00 PM.
•
Employees with flexible or remote work arrangements must still be reachable during core hours.
Attendance Expectations
•
Employees are expected to be at their workstation and ready to work at the start of their scheduled shift.
•
Tardiness is defined as arriving more than 10 minutes after the scheduled start time.
•
Excessive tardiness (3 or more instances in a 30-day period) will result in a formal warning.
•
Employees are expected to work their full contracted hours each week. Leaving early without approval counts as an absence.
Reporting an Absence
•
Employees must notify their direct manager of any unplanned absence before 9:00 AM on the day of the absence, via phone call or Slack message.
•
Email alone is not sufficient for unplanned absences.
•
For planned absences, PTO must be submitted and approved in advance via the HR portal.
•
Failure to report an absence without notification is considered a no-call/no-show and may result in disciplinary action.
Types of Absences
Excused Absences
The following absences are considered excused when properly reported:
•
Approved PTO or vacation
•
Sick leave (with notification by 9:00 AM)
•
Approved parental, bereavement, or jury duty leave
•
Medical appointments (employees should try to schedule outside core hours when possible)
•
Company-approved remote work days
Unexcused Absences
The following are considered unexcused:
•
No-call/no-show (absent without notification)
•
Tardiness not communicated in advance
•
Leaving early without manager approval
•
Exhausting all sick days and continuing to take unplanned sick leave
Sick Leave
•
Employees receive 10 sick days per calendar year (separate from PTO).
•
Sick days reset on January 1 and do not carry over.
•
Employees absent for more than 3 consecutive days due to illness must provide a doctor's note upon return.
•
Sick leave may not be used for non-illness personal days (use PTO for that purpose).
Bereavement Leave
•
Employees receive 5 paid bereavement days for the death of an immediate family member (spouse, child, parent, sibling).
•
3 paid bereavement days for the death of an extended family member (grandparent, aunt, uncle, in-law).
•
1 paid day for the death of a close friend or colleague, subject to manager approval.
•
Additional unpaid leave may be requested and is subject to manager and HR approval.
Jury Duty
•
Employees called for jury duty will receive their full pay for up to 15 business days.
•
Employees must provide a copy of the jury summons to HR as soon as it is received.
•
If jury duty extends beyond 15 days, the employee may use PTO or request unpaid leave.
Attendance Tracking
•
Attendance is tracked through the HR portal time-keeping system.
•
Managers are responsible for reviewing and approving weekly timesheets by noon on Monday for the previous week.
•
Discrepancies must be reported to HR within 5 business days.
Disciplinary Process for Attendance Issues
Occurrence
Action
1st unexcused absence or 3 tardiness instances
Verbal warning from manager
2nd unexcused absence within 90 days
Written warning, placed in personnel file
3rd unexcused absence within 90 days
Final written warning or suspension
4th unexcused absence within 90 days
Termination
Managers have discretion to consider circumstances and escalate or de-escalate as appropriate.
Contact
For attendance questions or to submit a leave request, contact hr@acmecorp.com or log in to the HR portal.
Public Holidays & Company Holidays Policy
Overview
This policy lists the official paid public holidays observed by Acme Corp. All full-time employees receive these days as paid time off. Part-time employees receive prorated holiday pay based on their scheduled hours.
